Report on the results of the parallel review of the management of the turnover tax of the Czech Republic and Germany
Preface
The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, emphasizes that the courts of auditors are entitled to examine the entire public finances.
The declaration requires the courts of auditors to have the power to scrutinise the tax collection as much as possible.
The Organization of the European Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) considers taxes an important part of public revenue.
The thematic focus of the 6th EUROSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, was the auditing of public revenues by the courts of auditors.
One of the most important steps towards optimising the audit work of the Court of Auditors is to develop a specific strategy for auditing public revenue.
This is particularly true of taxes as the largest source of public revenue with a high risk of default.
As the national economies become increasingly interconnected and interdependent, a situation may arise in which the national auditors can only carry out their audit work in cooperation with the auditors of other States.
The test of internationally organised fraud, which can lead to significant losses of income in many countries, can be considered as an example.
Cooperation between the authorities is required in the fight against such crimes.
Auditing bodies in this area must be prepared to work closely together.
The idea of auditing the turnover tax and the MIAS system came up at the 6th EUROSAI Congress in Bonn, which was carried out in cooperation with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Audit Office.
In the course of a thorough preparation, the participating courts had to first familiarise themselves with the legal framework and procedures of the sales tax administration in the Czech Republic and in Germany.
Based on the analysis of the available information, we selected the subjects for the examination planning.
Achieving effective and effective management of VAT is a long-standing problem, and individual states (in particular the EC Member States) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify the collection of VAT and create greater transparency in this area.
We are convinced that the results of our audit will not only improve the work of the financial administration, but also provide the basis for a proposal for an improved system of international exchange of information.
Report on the results of the parallel review of the management of the turnover tax of the Czech Republic and Germany
Introduction
Reference number: CZ) 06 / 27 (DE) VIII 2 - 2005 - 1215
Subject of examination:
(CZ) Management of sales tax after the Czech Republic's accession to the European Union
(De) Examination of administrative cooperation in the field of VAT in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 and 1925 / 2004
The Commission's audit objective:
(CZ) The purpose of the examination in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedures applied by the tax administration in the area of turnover tax, following the integration of the Czech Republic into the common internal market of the European Community (hereinafter "EC") with the free movement of goods and services and the use of MIAS1, in particular the control of the application of the VAT exemption for intra-Community supplies.
(De) The aim of the audit was to examine the system of intra-Community VAT control with a focus on mutual assistance in the area of VAT in accordance with the above-mentioned regulations.
As a result of the audit, weaknesses should be identified and recommendations made to remedy them.
VAT Information Exchange System The audits were carried out on the basis of an agreement concluded on 8 June 2006 by the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic ("NK") and the Federal Court of Justice ("BRH") of the Federal Republic of Germany.
The focus of the cooperation was the review of selected business transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany, the utilization of information obtained through international administrative assistance between the financial administrations and the comparison of the turnover tax management systems in the two states.
A joint final report on the results of the tests was prepared within the meaning of European guideline 31 for the implementation of the INTOSAI test standards.
The audited period covered the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005.
Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel examination
The parallel audit of the sales tax administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two courts.
In addition to the focus on "exchange of information" in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 and the Commission in 1925 / 2004, other closely related aspects have also been examined, such as the registration of tax collectors, tax returns and summary reports.
In addition, the audit also covered the legal situation for cross-border passenger transport by buses and the comparison of statistics.
When comparing the systems of VAT administrations in the two states, differences were found in the following areas:
1) Registration for VAT purposes.
Whereas in Germany, entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, among others, the essential criterion for registration is exceeding the VAT threshold set by the VAT law.
In the Czech Republic, tax collectors receive only one tax identification number, which they also use for intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, the tax collector receives a tax number valid only for domestic transactions for the purposes of sales tax.
If the German tax collector wants to carry out intra-Community transactions, he must apply for a special identification number, the so-called VAT ID number.
As there are problems with the different registration procedures, the rules should be standardised within the EC (see 4.1).
2) Cross-border passenger transport by bus.
In the Czech Republic, the cross-border carriage of passengers by buses is exempt from VAT, but there is a right to deduct VAT.
In Germany, if the route passes through Germany, the transport service is subject to turnover tax.
Efforts should be made at the EC level to standardise the situation in accordance with Article 393 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006 on the common turnover tax system (see 4.2).
3) Tax returns.
Whereas in the Czech Republic, tax collectors only have to file VAT returns for periods of under-age taxation (month or quarter), tax collectors in Germany have tax returns (monthly or quarterly).
Pre-registration of sales tax and after the end of the calendar year a declaration of the annual turnover tax.
In contrast to the Czech Republic, tax collectors in Germany are required to submit pre-tax VAT declarations by electronic means.
The introduction of the electronic tax declaration system in the Czech Republic would improve the effectiveness of the Czech tax administration (see 4.3).
4) Summary messages.
While tax collectors in the Czech Republic are required to submit their Comprehensive Reports to the tax authorities, German tax collectors are required to submit the Comprehensive Reports to the CLO2.
Accordingly, the information from the Comprehensive Notices will be available immediately after filing them in the Czech Republic.
The information from the Comprehensive Notices will only be available to German consumers after their processing by the CLO.
In order to combat VAT fraud, updated information on intra-Community transactions is required as soon as possible.
The monthly submission of summary reports would shorten the period between the time of turnover and the update of MIAS data.
This would allow a timely assessment of taxation in the purchaser's Member State (see 4.4), but only if all EC Member States introduce the same deadlines.
5) International exchange of information in the field of sales tax.
For incoming requests for information, the Czech CLO will monitor compliance with the three-month period.
The German CLO does not monitor the processing times.
As a result, the German financial administration has completed a significantly lower percentage of requests for information received within the prescribed period.
Due to these problems, the BRH has recommended to the German CLO a continuous monitoring of the deadlines (see 4.6).
6) Risk management.
Each of the two Member States is developing its own risk management system (RMS) with appropriate strengths and weaknesses.
The NCA and BRH point out that an effective RMS cannot be developed by a Member State alone.
Successful criteria, elements or approaches of an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in all EC Member States. Otherwise, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5.).
Within the framework of the cooperation, the two courts of auditors examined selected cases of intra-Community transactions, which were carried out between Czech and German tax entities.
Of these, 31 cases were jointly investigated using the legal possibilities of the CLO, in which there were doubts about the correct taxation or the suspicion of VAT fraud.
The Court of Auditors found that:
In some cases, the tax authorities made use of the information obtained during the international exchange of information and re-established the value added tax liability of the persons concerned.
In these cases, the tax collectors had either unlawfully claimed the VAT exemption or not declared the purchase of goods in their VAT declaration.
In some cases, people could not use the information obtained during the exchange of information because it was incomplete or incomprehensible.
In other cases, the information could not be used because of different legal requirements in the two Member States.
In some cases, the financial administration of another Member State refused to provide information.
Some cases have been uncovered in which tax collectors have shown inaccurate sales in their summary reports.
As a result, the data in MIAS were correspondingly erroneous, so that the clerks (the case manager) had to investigate in these cases (see 6).
Examination procedure
Testing in the CR
The audit was carried out between June 2006 and March 2007 by Department II - "State Budget Revenue" and the regional audit departments of Central Bohemia, Northwest Bohemia, South Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and North Moravia.
The audited bodies were: The Ministry of Finance and the 10 departments Humpolec, Jihlava, Kadaň, Liberec, Nymburk, Otrokovice, Prague 1, Prague 4, Sokolov and Třinec.
The College of the NCP approved the findings of the audit on 23 April 2007.
Examination procedures in Germany
The audit was carried out between July 2006 and February 2007 in the field of traffic taxes and employees of the associated PÄB Berlin, Frankfurt / Main and Munich.
It was part of the work plan for 2006 and was therefore announced to the Ministry of Finance (BMF) in 2006.
After a trial phase, the actual testing started in the fourth quarter of 2006.
According to the cases selected by the BRH and later by the NK, the BRH had to announce the examination in several federal states.
Apart from interviews in the BMF and the CLO, the test was carried out in the following federal states:
Baden-Württemberg, Bavaria, Hamburg, Lower Saxony, North Rhine-Westphalia, Rhineland-Palatinate and Saxony.
Tax files from the following cases have been included in the audit:
Bruchsal, Ettlingen, Freudenstadt, Karlsruhe-Stadt, Leonberg, Mühlacker, Singen, Tuttlingen, Cham, Fürstenfeldbruck, Munich corporations, Munich II, IV and Munich V, Starnberg, Hamburg-Altona, Hamburg-Hansa, Hamburg-Mitte, Hamburg-Nord and Hamburg for large companies, Hanover-Nord, Winsen-Luhe, Bonn-Innenstadt, Cologne-Aug.
In addition, discussions were held with the City of Augsburg, Aurich, Düsseldorf-Altstadt, Eisleben, Kelheim and Verden.
The results were reported to the BMF in May 2007.
Cooperation between the two courts
In the run-up to the parallel audit, several meetings were held between representatives of both audit bodies.
The participants in these meetings became familiar with the organisation of the financial administration, the legislation on VAT and the system of the VAT administration in each other country.
The subject of the test phase was agreed at the meeting in May 2006.
The results of the test phase were evaluated at the next joint meeting in August 2006.
At this meeting, a timetable for further proceedings was drawn up and the following examination topics for parallel examinations were determined: 1.
Registration of tax collectors.
2.
Cross-border passenger transport by bus - legislation in the Czech Republic and Germany.
3. International exchange of information, in particular the actions of the financial officers in the processing of requests for information and the verification of selected problems mentioned in the requests for information, as well as spontaneous information between the Czech Republic and Germany.
4. Tax returns.
5.
Summary messages.
6.
Statistical information on deliveries and purchases between the Czech Republic and Germany.
7. Risk management in the area of sales tax.
At a meeting in December 2006 to coordinate the further examination of the NK and BRH, both sides familiarised themselves with the examination procedure in the Czech Republic and Germany and discussed the results of the parallel tests that have already been achieved.
