An entrepreneur with legal domicile, registered office or establishment in the Czech Republic, whose turnover in the last 12 consecutive calendar months exceeds the amount of CZK 1 000 000, will be paid on the first day of the third month after the month in which he has crossed the threshold (Section 94 (1) of Law No. 235 / 2004 Coll., concerning VAT; hereinafter "Law No. 235 / 2004").
The person concerned must apply for registration within 15 days of the end of the month in which he / she has exceeded the registration threshold.
The current legislation does not allow the retroactive registration of tax collectors if they have exceeded the application deadline for registration.
An entrepreneur with legal domicile, registered office or establishment in the Czech Republic, who provides services exempt from VAT or VAT with the right to deduct VAT, must register for VAT even if his turnover does not exceed CZK 1 million, but he meets other requirements mentioned in Law No. 235 / 2004.
An entrepreneur with legal domicile, registered office or establishment in the Czech Republic, who does not meet any of the requirements set out in the law, can voluntarily apply for VAT registration.
The registration procedure according to Law No. 337 / 1992 begins with the receipt of the application from the local financial officer responsible for registration.
If you want to register voluntarily for VAT, you must specify in your application the date on which you apply for registration as a VAT collector.
The financial officer must check the information provided by the entrepreneur, i.e. the completed application for registration with all investments.
If he has doubts about the information given in it, he must ask the applicant to explain, supplement or prove the information provided.
If, by verification, the financial officer has established that the entrepreneur meets the requirements for registration, he must issue a written notice of registration and the allocation of a tax number.
In the notice, the financial officer must indicate the date of entry into force of the VAT registration and the period of assessment for the VAT.
The period of disposition is the calendar quarter, unless the turnover of the entrepreneur for the previous calendar year has reached the amount of at least CZK 10 million.
If this is the case, the period of disposition is the calendar month.
An entrepreneur whose turnover reached at least CZK 2 000 000 in the preceding calendar year is entitled to choose the calendar month as the accounting period and to inform the financial officer of this change.
The issue of a tax number in the registration notice is always constitutive.
The tax collector must provide the tax number for each communication (including payments) with the tax officer, in addition, in cases where a specific law requires it (e.g. Law No. 235 / 2004, concerning the preparation of tax documents) 3.
The tax number contains the coding "CZ" and a basic component in the form of a general identification mark.
In the case of natural persons, this is the number of the birth certificate or another general identification mark, as determined by a specific law. In the case of legal entities, the general identification mark is the company identification number (in accordance with the provisions of § 33 (12) of Law No. 337 / 1992).
If the entrepreneur has not fulfilled his obligation, despite a request from the financial officer, the local finance officer must register him ex officio.
A notice will also be issued to the person responsible for the tax.
In the Czech Republic, every businessman approved for business operations receives a tax number at his first registration for any type of tax.
This also applies to registration as a VAT payer.
According to Law No. 235 / 2004, which entered into force on January 1, 2005, in the case of non-compliance with the VAT law, the tax officer may require that the taxable person have up to 10% of the revenue from the tax-deductible turnover, which the person concerned has made unlawfully without taxation in 2004, for the period from the date from which the entrepreneur should have been registered as tax collector by the date of registration.
The payment of the fixed amount is considered a tax payment within the meaning of § 98 (3) of Law No. 235 / 2004, i.e. it is not a fine or penalty.
If the legal requirements are met, the registration of a VAT person can be deleted for two reasons:
(1)
Deletion of the registration at the request of the person responsible for the tax, i.e. mainly for the reason that the turnover does not reach the threshold for registration (§ 106 (1) of Law 235 / 2004).
A tax collector can apply for the deletion of his registration at the earliest one year after the date of entry into force mentioned in the registration notice.
2) the deletion of the registration ex officio (§ 106 (7) of Law no. 235 / 2004), if: A) the tax collector failed to perform in the period of 12 consecutive months and did not inform the tax officer of the reasons why, b) the tax collector did not fulfil his obligations according to Law no. 235 / 2004, c) the previous tax officer did not meet the conditions for the tax avoidance.
B) tax collectors without legal domicile, registered office or business premises in the Czech Republic A person who is registered for tax purposes in another Member State and in the Czech Republic does not have legal domicile, place of business or establishment, or a tax-exempt foreigner who provides services in the Czech Republic and who has to make a tax declaration and pay taxes for these services or supplies in accordance with section 108 of the Law no. 235 / 2004 ("non-resident company").
He must file an application for registration with the Prague 1 FA at the latest on the day of the delivery.
In this request, he is entitled to indicate all the VAT Idol allocated to him in other Member States or third countries.
If a non-resident entrepreneur applies for registration later than the day of the first tax-deductible provision of services in the Czech Republic, the Prague 1 FA must register him retroactively, since he became subject to VAT according to Law No. 235 / 2004 on the day of the first tax-deductible provision of services in the Czech Republic.
In the case of a retrospective registration, the Prague 1 FA has to demand a certificate (invoices or written explanations) from the operators concerned for the proof of performance.
If a non-resident entrepreneur requests registration in the Czech Republic before the first performance of a service, the Prague 1 FA has to demand the submission of the performance-based contract documents.
As of December 31, 2004, 473 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered with the Prague FA 1, of which 124 were from Germany. As of December 31, 2005, a total of 951 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered, 233 of whom were from Germany.
In accordance with the provisions of § 106 (9) of Law 235 / 2004, the tax officer is authorised to delete the registration of a non-resident businessman on 31 January of the following calendar year if he does not accept the obligation to file tax filings or declarations and to pay tax.
When examining the NICK, it turned out that in the case of the submission of a tax return by mail with dispatch abroad on 25 January, i.e. in accordance with the mandatory deadline for the submission of a tax return, this declaration had not yet been received by the FA until 31 January.
In cases where these facts, which are relevant to the possibility of cancelling the registration, become known to the FA later than 31 January, it is no longer possible to delete the registration of the non-resident businessman for VAT in the Czech Republic in the calendar year in question.
Registration of tax collectors in Germany
According to the provisions of the tax regulation (§ 137, 138 AO), every business must be registered with the municipality and / or the competent tax office.
This application must be made at the latest one month after commencement of business.
The municipality forwards the registration to the tax authorities.
If the competent tax office determines that a business activity has been commenced but has not been notified, it may also register the tax collector retroactively.
Tax collectors in Germany, regardless of whether they are resident or non-resident, are liable to the registration of Zwekke for VAT if they fulfil the requirements of Section 2 of the German VAT Act (VAT Act).
This does not depend on the amount of turnover achieved.
There is no voluntary registration in Germany.
Foreign-based entrepreneurs are responsible for special requirements.
For example, FA ChemnitzSüd is responsible for those entrepreneurs who are based in the Czech Republic.
As of 30 April 2004, there were a total of 295 Czech entrepreneurs registered there; 1,050 Czech entrepreneurs were registered there as of 1 March 2006.
According to the BRH, these individuals with special responsibilities repeatedly refused the registration of so-called false self-employed persons residing in the new Central and Eastern European member states of the EC.
Since the free movement of workers is still restricted after the accession of these ten countries to the European Union, these self-employed people tried to avoid these restrictions by setting up their own business.
These (appearance) self-employed persons do not fulfil the requirements of § 2 UStG for recognition as entrepreneurs, since they usually depend on a single client, who determines their working hours and the type of work they perform.
In order to be registered, the entrepreneur must fill in a questionnaire from the competent FA and provide information on the company and the business carried out.
The questionnaire is a binding form for all people in Germany.
It will be processed either in specific organizational units within the organization or in the organizational units that are generally responsible for tax claims.
With the help of this pressure, a risk assessment for the individual tax collector is carried out before the allocation of a tax number.
The establishment of the tax number for domestic transactions is based on certain requirements:
The first three digits are the identification number for the competent FA, the following three (or four) digits indicate which department is responsible within the FA, the following five (or four) digits are the identifier for the tax collector, the last digit is always a check digit.
If an entrepreneur wants to participate in intra-Community trade, he needs a VAT ID to be able to make tax-free intra-Community deliveries.
This will be allocated by the CLO on request if the entrepreneur is registered in Germany for sales tax purposes.
The VAT ID number is automatically allocated by the CLO when the tax collector declares intra-Community deliveries in his VAT pre-registration or in his VAT annual declaration.
The USt IdNr. consists of the country code (DE) and a sequence of nine digits.
The registration of an entrepreneur can be deleted: 1. On request (for example, if he ceases to do business), but only after the completion of all tax procedures (accounting for all financial years) or 2. If the financial administration determines that he is no longer in business.
As a rule, the validity of the VAT ID number depends on the validity of the VAT number.
In such cases, Fähr must notify the CLO of the deletion of the VAT number so that the validity of the VAT ID number can be terminated at that time.
According to the VAT Act (§ 19 (1) UStG), domestic tax collectors do not have to pay VAT in the following cases: 1. The turnover of the previous calendar year plus the turnover tax incurred on it did not exceed €17,500 and 2. The amount of €50,000 will probably not be exceeded in the following year.
The so-called small business owners are not entitled to charge VAT to other entrepreneurs, nor are they entitled to deduct VAT.
Although they do not have to pay sales tax, small business owners are required to register with the tax office and make an annual VAT return.
A small business owner can explain the non-application of § 19 (1) UStG.
This declaration is binding for the next five years.
He may then charge the sales tax and deduct the pretax.
Non-resident tax collectors can appoint a fiscal representative (§ 22a UStG).
The prerequisite for this is that they exclusively carry out tax-free transactions and waive the deduction of input tax.
The fiscal representative meets the tax requirements of the foreign entrepreneur, so he does not have to register for VAT purposes.
The invoices state that a fiscal representative has been appointed.
Comparison and evaluation
The situation in the two states is different.
Whereas in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the first requirement for registration (among others) is to exceed the threshold specified in the VAT law.
If an entrepreneur does not cross this threshold, he can register voluntarily.
The registration procedure in Germany is standardised, but differences can occur due to different organizational structures in the individual federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the tax collector receives a tax number at the time of his first registration for any tax.
In the case of its registration for VAT, this tax number also applies to intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, an entrepreneur who registers for sales tax purposes receives a tax number exclusively for domestic German sales.
If the German entrepreneur wants to carry out intra-Community transactions, he must specifically apply for the allocation of a VAT ID number.
Both the NCA and the BRH noted that the German two-tier registration system in other Member States, such as the Czech Republic, which has a single identification number for both national VAT registration and intra-Community transactions, can lead to significant misunderstandings.
On the other hand, the two-tier system allows for retroactive registration (national registration) in cases where the tax collector does not register his business with the municipality or the competent FA.
This retroactive registration allows for a true tendency to value added tax for previous accounting periods, in particular an accurate estimate of the value added tax debt.
Since the different registration procedures cause problems, the rules should be standardised throughout the EC.
The German parliament recently approved the introduction of a tax identification number.
This is to be allocated by the Federal Central Tax Office to each natural person after birth.
This number applies to natural persons residing in Germany for life.
If a natural person takes up a business, the competent FA applies for a commercial tax identification number, which serves as the VAT ID number.
In the future, therefore, there should be no delay between the national registration of a tax collector and the allocation of the VAT ID number.
Work has not yet been completed on the implementation of an IT procedure for managing the numbers.
Cross-border passenger transport by bus
Legislation in the Czech Republic
According to the provisions of Section 70 of Law 235 / 2004, since 1 May 2004 the carriage of passengers between individual Member States and between Member States and third countries in the Czech Republic has been exempt from VAT and there is a right to deduct VAT.
The exemption from VAT also applies if the carriage of persons registered as tax collectors in other Member States or foreigners who are domestically taxable is carried out.
The return journey is considered to be a separate carriage.
If non-resident operators in the Czech Republic carry out no economic activity other than the cross-border carriage of passengers by bus, they are not entitled to be registered in the Czech Republic as subject to turnover tax.
Cross-border passenger transport in the Czech Republic has been exempted from VAT in accordance with the Act on the accession of the Czech Republic, Annex V, Chapter 5 (1) (b), which states:
"For the purpose of applying Article 28 (3) (b) of Directive 77 / 388 / EEC, the Czech Republic may, in accordance with Article 17 of Annex F of the Directive, maintain the exemption for cross-border transport of persons until the condition of Article 28 (4) of the Directive is fulfilled or as long as the same exemption is applied by any of the current Member States."
The legal regulations in Germany
According to Article 46 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006, as implemented in Germany by section 3b (1) of the UStG, a transport service is carried out where the carriage is effected.
Accordingly, German taxation does not distinguish between domestic and cross-border passenger transport.
Only the domestic part of the transport service is subject to tax in Germany.
German taxation also does not distinguish between resident and non-resident (bus) operators.
If a non-resident tax collector transports persons through Germany, the part of the carriage that falls on Germany is considered to be a tax-deductible carriage.
Before providing his services in Germany, the non-resident entrepreneur must report his intention to provide passenger transport services to the relevant FA.
It registers it for tax purposes (compare 4.1.2) and issues a special certificate for each bus named in the tax registration.
The entrepreneur must state his tax-deductible transport services in a German VAT declaration.
As of 1 March 2006, 741 Czech bus operators were registered with the Chemnitz South FA.
If the transport service is provided for a domestic entrepreneur, the non-resident tax collector does not have to pay the VAT himself to the FA.
In its place, the domestic buyer of the services must pay the VAT to the tax office and the net amount charged to the non-resident taxpayer, which is referred to as the "transfer of tax liability" and is in accordance with Article 196 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC.
In addition to the registration by a non-resident tax collector and his income tax return, the German financial administration has several means of verifying the accuracy of the tax return with regard to tax-deductible transport of persons:
Mobile control groups of the customs check the certificates of buses registered abroad, which are used for the transport of passengers through Germany.
After each inspection, the mobile control groups send an inspection report to the competent FA.
If the bus driver does not have a valid certificate, the mobile control group can require the bus driver to pay VAT before continuing his journey.
The non-resident tax collector can deduct the value added tax thus paid from the tax debt indicated in his VAT return.
If the FA has doubts about the accuracy of a VAT declaration, it can order an examination to take place in the FA, or it can use the means of mutual assistance mentioned in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 (see point 4.6).
Even if the foreign tax collector refuses to pay the legally established VAT, the FA may ask for mutual assistance in accordance with Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC.
The BRH considers these means of mutual assistance in tax matters for the verification of the VAT declaration or compliance with the tax rules by a non-resident bus operator to be too costly in relation to the small amount of turnover tax on tax-deductible passenger transport.
In particular, the auditing of the books of a non-resident tax collector costs disproportionately for the tax collector himself and for the financial administration.
The latter must check foreign books, which requires knowledge not only of the foreign language, but also of foreign accounting principles.
Accordingly, such an examination will require more time than a resident tax collector, although the examination will be limited to the transport of persons in Germany.
On the other hand, the non-resident tax collector must accept not only the audit rights of his national financial administration, but also those of the other Member States, as far as he carries out personal transport there.
In addition, for each Member State in which a single transport of persons is carried out, the tax collector must comply with all existing tax rules in the various languages and on the forms of the financial administrations of the EC Member States concerned.
Thus, the correct taxation of cross-border passenger transport services leads to a disproportionate administrative burden.
Comparison and evaluation
The legal situation is different in the two states.
In the Czech Republic, passenger transport between different EC Member States and between Member States and third countries is exempt from VAT under the law on the Czech Republic's accession to the EU.
In Germany, transport services are subject to a turnover tax in accordance with the route covered by the German territory.
If a non-resident tax collector provides such a service for the first time, he must first report it to the competent FA.
This registers the tax collector, who has to declare the tax-deductible portion of the transport performance in a tax declaration in Germany.
Law enforcement in Germany is very time-consuming.
At least three out of four Czech tax collectors registered with the Chemnitz-South FA have the transport of persons as a business purpose.
The amount of tax in question is quite low in relation to the administrative burden.
The Member States - which collect the turnover tax in accordance with Article 46 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006 on the common VAT system - have a high administrative burden in relation to the relevant tax revenue.
In order to avoid the disproportionate cost of VAT, cross-border transport of passengers should only be subject to tax in one Member State.
This could be the state where the transport starts or where the service provider resides.
Such a type of taxation would require an amendment to Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006.
Sales tax returns
Filing and processing of VAT returns in the Czech Republic
Unless the law specifies otherwise, even if no tax debt has been incurred, the entrepreneur is contracted to file a VAT return on the form provided by the Ministry of Finance within 25 days after the expiration of the tax period.
The tax liability arises at the end of the period for filing the VAT return. The exception to this rule is the VAT on the import of goods according to law 235 / 2004, where the due date of the tax is determined by the customs regulations.
If, as a result of higher-than-average deductible taxes, there is a claim for a refund, this amount will be refunded to the person responsible for the tax within 30 days after fixing this deduction, without the need to make an application.
The deadline is not applied in cases where the tax officer initiates a tax procedure with regard to the tax debt of the person liable for the tax.
Pursuant to section 73 (11) of Law 235 / 2004, the claim for deduction can be asserted at the latest with the regular tax return for the last tax period of the calendar year in which the claim for deduction was made.
After the expiration of this period, the deduction can still be claimed within three years after the end of the tax period, in which the claim would have been possible for the first time.
For this, however, it is necessary to present a supplementary VAT declaration.
An amendment to Law No. 235 / 2004, which came into force on 1 January 2005, allows the filing of a supplementary VAT return only for the period in which the claim for deduction of VAT could have been made for the first time.
A tax collector must make a supplementary VAT declaration if: (A) the sum of the corrections leads to an increase in the tax debt, (b) he makes corrections which do not change the last known tax debt, but only change the previous information, (c) he makes adjustments to the VAT rate and the tax liability in accordance with section 49 of Law No. 235 / 2004.
A tax collector can make a supplementary VAT declaration if the sum of the corrections reduces the tax liability.
The tax collector must submit the supplementary tax return by the end of the month following the month in which the relevant facts were established.
The sales tax declaration can be made electronically either on the Internet or via data carriers.
Internet delivery can take place with or without a certified electronic signature.
If it is done without an electronic signature, it must also be submitted on a data carrier.
The form for the VAT declaration contains separate lines for the indication of the value of intra-Community deliveries and purchases.
The value of related services must be specified in separate lines of the VAT return.
Some categories are used for automated primary checks within the ATIS system.
