Filing and processing of VAT returns in Germany
In Germany, a distinction is made between the monthly or quarterly VAT pre-registration and the annual VAT declaration.
Those tax collectors who are licensed to submit VAT pre-registration must nevertheless make an annual VAT return.
Even small business owners who are not contracted to pay VAT will have to make an annual VAT return.
Tax collectors are in principle required to file a sales tax notice by the 10th day after the end of the calendar quarter in which the sales tax is incurred (§ 18 (2) UStG).
However, if the VAT debt amounted to more than €6,136 in the previous year, or if it is a newly founded company, the entrepreneur is required to submit monthly pre-tax declarations by the 10th day after the expiration of the respective month at the latest.
The person paying the tax can also opt for the payment of monthly VAT pre-registration if he has been refunded more than €6,136 in the previous year (§ 18 (2a) UStG).
If the annual turnover tax is not more than €512, neither VAT pre-registration nor VAT returns have to be made.
A resulting value-added tax debt must be paid 10 days after the end of the tax period.
A refund can lead to a more thorough audit by the financial administration.
(Legal) deadlines for the processing of VAT returns and for the refund of VAT overpayments do not exist.
In order to obtain a timely refund, a security can be offered for the refund amount.
In principle, VAT returns, including refund cases, must be processed quickly.
The German VAT Act allows for an extension of these (surrender or payment) deadlines (§ 18 (6) UStG).
The extension of the deadline must be requested separately.
If it is granted, the VAT pre-registration and the corresponding payments may be made one month later. However, in the case of monthly reports, a special advance payment has to be made.
This payment will be calculated against the VAT debt established for the pre-registration period in December.
If an error is discovered, the entrepreneur must make a corrected VAT declaration.
There is no "supplementary" VAT declaration.
Once the VAT declaration to be submitted by 31 May of the following year has been submitted to the tax office, the entrepreneur can no longer correct an incorrect VAT declaration, but only the incorrect annual VAT declaration.
Correction of this VAT declaration to the advantage or disadvantage of the person responsible for the tax is possible within four years after the expiration of the year in which the first VAT declaration was made.
After the expiration of this four-year period, a VAT declaration can usually only be corrected in cases of careless tax reduction or tax evasion.
Tax collectors must submit pre-tax declarations by electronic means.
The pledges can grant exceptions to this rule in order to avoid undue hardship.
The annual VAT declaration can be made in paper form or via the Internet with or without certification.
If the submission takes place without certification, the tax collector must make the declaration on paper and with his / her personal signature.
If no VAT declarations or declarations are made, the tax administration is entitled to make a rough estimate of the turnover achieved by the tax collective6.
In the case of late payment, a delay surcharge can be imposed on the tax payer (up to 10% of the tax liability or up to €25,000).
In an earlier investigation, the BRH found that the airlines often do not charge this delay surcharge.
In the cases where the fees are collected, the amount is fixed in an inconsistent and arbitrary manner.
The delay surcharge therefore misses its purpose of reducing the average delay, in particular in the submission of the annual VAT declaration.
The form of the VAT declaration contains separate lines for value information on intra-Community deliveries or purchases.
There are also separate lines for the provision of services.
Non-taxable transactions are to be specified in a separate line of the VAT declaration.
The VAT returns submitted on paper must either be scanned or electronically recorded by specially appointed personnel.
The data of electronically submitted tax returns are immediately available to the financial administration.
