Submission and processing of summary reports in the Czech Republic
In accordance with the provisions of Section 102 of Law 235 / 2004, an entrepreneur who supplies goods to a person registered in another Member State for tax purposes is required to make such summary declarations (hereinafter "ZM").
The value of the delivered goods is always given in Czech currency in the ZM, according to the VAT IdNr7, the individual tax collectors under which they are registered in the other Member State.
Information on services is not provided in the ZM.
The taxable persons with a calendar monthly or quarterly period of taxation have to hand over the ZM to the local FA at the latest on the 25th day after the expiration of each quarter.
Incorrect data must be corrected in a correction ZM within 15 days after the error has been detected.
Erroneous data in the ZM are always replaced by data from the correction ZM.
Similar to tax returns, tax collectors can also submit the ZM electronically.
If a tax collector does not issue a ZM or correction ZM, even though it is provided for by law no. 235 / 2004, the financial officer must ask him to surrender the ZM in question and assign it to the consequences of the non-payment. In the case of non-monetary claims, the financial officer is authorised to repeatedly impose fines of up to 2 million CZK, in accordance with section 37 of Law No 337 / 1992.
The NICK found in its audit that the tax authorities mostly did not use their power to impose fines against their defaulting taxpayers.
In particular, the tax collectors are not sufficiently motivated to fulfil their obligations when submitting the ZM, since the omitted payment of an ZM does not affect the amount of their VAT debt.
Pursuant to section 102 (5) of Law 235 / 2004, the financial officer is required to check the information in the ZM or the correction ZM, to remove all ambiguity and to use the information to fix the tax debt.
