The clerks there must investigate the discrepancies.
Three different situations can occur:
A) The value indicated by the Czech purchaser in the relevant categories of its VAT declaration is lower than the value of the deliveries indicated by suppliers from other EC Member States.
In this case, the financial officer will check the accuracy of the information.
B) The difference is zero.
This situation may result either from a change in the information within the EC (the foreign supplier corrects its ZM) or from a change in the information in the VAT declaration (the Czech tax collector in the meantime makes a supplementary VAT declaration on his own initiative).
In this case, it is at the discretion of the financial officer to check the accuracy of the information in the VAT declaration.
C) The value of the goods purchased from other Member States, which the Czech tax collector has indicated in his VAT declaration, is higher than the value of the shipments reported by suppliers of the other EC Member States.
Again, it is at the discretion of the financial officer to check the accuracy of the information.
After reviewing the differences and clarifying the reasons for their occurrence, the finance officer enters the results of his review into ATIS.
These results will be transmitted to the CLO.
