Submission and processing of Comprehensive Notices in Germany
Operators who make intra-Community deliveries from Germany to other EC Member States or take part in triangular transactions are required to submit quarterly ZM, which lists intra-Community deliveries to purchasers (§ 18a (1) UStG).
The ZM must be delivered no later than the 10th day of the month following the calendar quarter concerned.
If a long-term extension is granted for the submission of sales tax pre-applications, this also applies to the ZM.
The ZM must be handed over to the CLO.
Since 1 January 2007, the electronic levy has been phased out.
The competent FA can allow exemptions for individual tax dodgers in order to avoid undue hardship.
If the person in charge of the tax notices that the ZM was defective, he is liable to make a correction ZM within one month.
In the case of non-payment of the ZM, the CLO initiates an enforcement procedure.
This includes the following steps: - first reminder - second reminder, together with the threat of a penalty payment being set and - fixing the penalty.
Although the German tax code allows a penalty of up to €25,000 (Section 329 AO) to be set, the CLO imposes fines of €125, 250 and 500 in three stages.
In addition, § 26a (1) No. 5 UStG specifies that the person liable to tax acts contrary to the law if he or she intentionally or recklessly fails to deliver a ZM correctly, completely or on time, or if he or she fails to correct an ZM in time.
This infringement can be punished with a fine of up to €5,000.
Data on intra-Community deliveries cannot be entered into the MIAS by the companies, because the CLO is exclusively responsible for processing the ZM.
The ZM data is only stored by the CLO.
The information from the Comprehensive Notices will only be available to the Fähr after their processing by the CLO.
The deadlines for processing ZM are laid down in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003.
ZM data must be stored within three months of the calendar quarter (in MIAS).
In the case of incorrect VAT number in the ZM of German tax collectors, the German CLO receives a message "O _ MCTL" from the other Member State.
The CLO then turns to the entrepreneur and asks for the correct data.
If the CLO fails to obtain the correct information, the case will be referred to the relevant FA.
It is then his job to request the right information.
In the course of its examination, the BRH found that most operators corrected the VAT ID number at the request of the CLO.
However, remembering, threatening and fixing up to three consecutive fines takes too much time when a tax collector may be involved in cross-border carousel fraud.
The cases that were ultimately reported to the competent authorities were usually completed within one to two months.
The competent FA refused exemption for the reported intra-Community deliveries in 73% of these expirations9.
If the tax collector presented the correct VAT ID number, the FA asked him to submit a corrected ZM to the CLO, because the tax authorities cannot correct the MIAS data themselves.
The BRH found that neither the FTE nor the CLO controlled the submission of the corrected ZM.
Therefore, the tax collectors often did not comply with the request. Since the CLO does not have access to the data of the VAT returns, there is no comparison of the information given in the VAT estimates or the VAT declaration on the delivery of goods with the corresponding data in the ZM before these data are transmitted to the CLO of the other Member States.
This comparison can only be carried out by the tax authorities, usually during the preparation of a special VAT check.
Data received from other Member States is processed by the CLO.
Incorrect VAT ID numbers are detected and reported to the Member States concerned.
The data will be used for the control of the tax on labour in the Member States.
