In the Czech Republic, tax collectors who have made intra-Community deliveries to a person registered in another Member State for VAT must submit a ZM to the local FA within 25 days of the end of the calendar quarter.
They process the ZM and forward the data to the CLO.
The values of intra-Community deliveries reported by the tax collectors in the ZM are compared with the values of intra-Community deliveries indicated by the same tax collectors in their VAT declarations.
The results of the comparison will be taken into account in the tax setting.
In Germany, tax collectors who have made intra-Community deliveries are liable to surrender quarterly ZM within the first 10 days of the following calendar quarter10.
Since 1 January 2007, tax collectors have been required to submit the ZM electronically to the CLO.
The data from the ZM will only be available to the users after its processing by the CLO.
Both in the Czech Republic and in Germany, the tax collectors only specify the deliveries of goods in the ZM.
The provision of services is not specified in the ZM. Unlike the Czech Fähr, the German Fähr cannot correct erroneous information in individual lines of the ZM.
Due to this limited access to the German MIAS data, incorrect VAT ID numbers were not corrected even if the person in charge reported the correct VAT ID number to the FA.
The German financial administration does not compare the information on intra-Community deliveries made by German tax collectors in their VAT pre-registration with the information provided by the relevant ZM.
Differences between the data of the pre-registration and the ZM are regularly not revealed before the German CLO transmits the MIAS data to other Member States.
Based on these findings by the BRH, it is evident that a comparison would improve the reliability of the MIAS data transmitted.
Data provided by other Member States on shipments of goods to Czech tax collectors will be compared in the Czech Republic with data on purchases of goods indicated by Czech tax collectors in their VAT returns.
The Czech CLO makes a separate comparison for each calendar quarter.
The most serious cases of deviation will be sent to the courts for examination.
Unlike the Czech financial administration, the German financial administration does not generally examine the taxation of intra-Community purchases.
Such a general control is only applied to tax collectors who are not fully entitled to deduct VAT.
In addition, the German tax administration controls the taxation of intra-Community purchases of other tax entities only if the RMS has drawn up an audit notice or the person responsible for the tax has already been selected for an audit.
This procedure relieves the pleading from clarifying the reasons for the differences that occur.
On the other hand, the detection of VAT fraud depends on the quality of the RMS.
In order to combat carousel fraud, updated information on intra-Community purchases must be available as soon as possible.
The current system of the ZM, in particular MIAS, provides the tax authorities with information that may well be half a year old.
This time delay could be reduced to up to four months if the tax collectors had to hand over monthly ZM.
The monthly levy would increase the bureaucratic burden only insignificantly, since most tax collectors in the Czech Republic and Germany are already liable for the submission of monthly VAT returns or pre-filings and for which ZM does not require more information than for VAT returns or preliminary declarations.
In order to avoid red tape, the ZM levy could be linked to the submission of VAT returns or advance declarations.
However, a monthly payment of ZM would cause more periodic discrepancies between the information on intra-Community deliveries and those on intra-Community purchases and increase the data flows between the CLOs.
In 2006, the Federal Government considered the general introduction of monthly ZM.
The implementation failed due to the concerns of the federal states.
They feared that a monthly transfer of MIAS data to the CLO of other Member States could lead to misunderstandings and confusion.
In order for the monthly surrender of ZM to be effective, it is necessary to agree on the common monthly levy at European level, so that a monthly update of the MIAS data is possible.
