The tax audit and tax investigation department carries out, among other things, risk analyses in the framework of the methodical management of tax audits, defines priorities for the work planning of the financial directorates with regard to the selection of cases to be examined, compiles risk analyses for the fight against tax evasion and, in this context, gathers information from the financial administration and other sources, and makes proposals for measures to combat tax evasion.
Tax Enforcement Services are established by the Finance Directors.Their tasks include the search for tax collectors and sectors that are risky in terms of the frequency of tax evasion (e.g. Internet stores, gold, pharmaceutical industry), the search for unregistered tax collectors (e.g. Internet services, labour mediation, electronic and print media, etc.), the investigation of suspicions in cases of fraud, and the information of local tax authorities.
Special exam units have been set up in 12 selected courses.
These have a regional competence and carry out tax audits outside the local area of jurisdiction of the Fähr on the basis of the corresponding authorisation.
The need to set up the special audit units resulted from the increase in new and "improved" forms of tax evasion, particularly in relation to chain transactions.
These special units examine according to the needs of tax investigators or focus on tax collectors with specific activities, multinational companies and tax collectors with particularly high turnover rates.
The following mechanisms for reducing the risks in the area of turnover tax have been integrated into the ATIS system: - the "credibility of VAT returns" to assess the risk effectiveness of tax returns, - the "selection of the taxable persons to be audited," whereby the taxable persons to be audited are selected on the basis of certain criteria, - the "MIAS" task, which allows financial officials to access the data provided by the other EC Member States.
The task "MIAS" makes possible, among other things, the following: - verification of the validity of the VAT Idn of taxable persons from other Member States, - confirmation of the value of the goods delivered to a Czech tax person, as stated in the ZM of all the suppliers of the tax person in question from other Member States, - preparation of a list of taxable persons who have not submitted the ZM, formal control of the data of the tax person in their tax person from other Member States, the creation of other Member States whose ZM does not appear in the information about the ZM of the ZM.
As part of their mission to combat tax evasion, financial officials have access to data from state agencies such as the Commercial Register, Land Registry Office, Motor Vehicle Registry, Commercial Register, etc.
More detailed information can be found in section 4.4.1 Submission and processing of the Comprehensive Notices in the Czech Republic.
Risk management in Germany
Due to their federal structure, in the Federal Republic of Germany, both the federal financial authorities (in particular the CLO) and the financial administrations of the 16 federal states are involved in the development and introduction of an RMS.
Although there are joint development working groups, neither the CLO nor the financial administrations of the federal states have a complete set of data.
At the level of the CLO, the unit ST I 2 (hereinafter referred to as the "KUSS" - Coordinating Unit for VAT Special Examinations and Tax Enforcement Measures) collects the audit findings on fraud cases in the OPUS database.
In cooperation with the countries, another database called ZAUBER has been set up at the KUSS, where the tax authorities can enter and retrieve the names of discovered missing traders or VAT cheats.
The CUSTOMER coordinates both related cases of VAT fraud at the national level and cases of cross-border VAT fraud.
The experience of the KUSS will be incorporated into the development of the RMS through their collaboration in the working groups.
In addition, experts from several other organizational units of the CLO and the BMF are also involved.
The CLO will carry out a formal review of the composition of VAT No. of other Member States that appear in the ZM of German taxpayers.
This formal review takes place before the ZM is transmitted to other Member States in order to improve the reliability of the MIAS data and thus its usefulness (see 4.4.2).
The validity of the VAT IdNo. referred to in the ZM is tested on the basis of the O _ MCTL identifiers supplied by the other Member States (for the procedure of rectifying invalid VAT Idn., see also 4.4.2).
In addition, the RMS of the CLO is based on the MIAS data transmitted by the other Member States and generates various types of messages on the discovery of suspected Missing Traders. Certain characteristics, which usually occur in carousel transactions, are used as clues.
In certain cases, the federal states are instructed to process these notices and have to report the outcome of their investigations to the CLO.
The BRH audit has confirmed that all available features must be included in order to be sufficiently likely to suggest a case of tax fraud (rather than focusing mainly on a company's turnover).
Accordingly, the BRH has recommended that the BMF work with combinations of different indications in the preparation of the messages.
The risk management system should also take into account other indicators, such as the payment behaviour of the tax payer, the economic sector or the company's shareholding.
A second level of risk management exists in the financial administrations of the federal states and focuses on the processing of sales tax pre-applications and annual declarations.
For example, the system creates a list of tax collectors who have indicated intra-Community deliveries in their VAT estimates or annual declarations.
This list will be sent to the CLO to monitor the full submission of the ZM.
Furthermore, in this type of risk management, the purchases indicated by the tax person in his annual VAT declaration are compared with the data in the MIAS.
The financial administrations of the federal states avoid a comparison of the quarterly data, since it would lead to too many discrepancies, which are due to factors other than tax evasion or tax fraud; e.g.:
- the supplier and the purchaser assume different times for the execution of the intra-Community turnover;
- different accounting and tax declaration of discounts and discounts.
In addition to comparing the data from the VAT returns with the MIAS data, many German states have certain risk management mechanisms, which are based on information in the VAT returns and certain other indications (e.g. company wording, the age of the owners / partners, the number of employees and the method of payment of the tax credit).
Bavaria has introduced a risk management system based on fixed rules, which allows a team of tax fraud specialists (hereinafter referred to as "risk managers") to program their own rules to identify suspected tax cheats.
This system is used to process VAT estimates.
This will give the competent FA the information of the RMS before the VAT is set.
Since this system is not capable of learning, the risk managers have to adjust the rules according to the feedback from the questions.
Mecklenburg-Vorpommern has developed an adaptive neural network based on the data of detected cases of deprivation.
Based on this data, the RMS is able to learn the characteristics of tax evasion.
The system compiles a monthly list of tax cases where there is evidence of tax evasion.
On the basis of this list, the competent authorities decide on the examination of the relevant tax collectors.
After the audit, the tax examiners must report their results so that the RMS can learn from the results of the tests it has proposed.
In North Rhine-Westphalia, an adaptive neural network is used in combination with a rule-based fuzzy system.
Based on many data from processed VAT returns and some other clues, this neuro-fuzzy system (also known as the data-mining system) calculates how likely it is that a tax collector is to be involved in tax fraud.
It then draws up a monthly list of suspected tax cheats.
On the basis of this list, the Fähr select the relevant tax collectors for examination and report the audit results to the data centre in question.
The introduction of these three RMS is under way in the federal states.
Since each of these three risk management systems is based on a different approach, the combination of all three systems for the fight against fraud appears to be effective.
It remains to be seen whether the desired effects will be achieved in actual use.
Comparison and evaluation
Although in this report it is not possible to deal with the specific criteria of the RMS in the Czech Republic and Germany, the NK and BRH have found that each Member State has developed its own RMS.
Like the different approaches in the three German federal states mentioned above, the RMS of each European state has its particular strengths and weaknesses.
An exchange of experience on new trends and new models of cross-border VAT fraud is currently taking place between the tax authorities of the European Member States.
VAT fraud - in particular carousel fraud - has turned out not to be a national problem, but a European one.
The people involved in the fraud coordinate their actions not only in one but in several Member States.
One Member State alone cannot develop an effective RMS.
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each EC Member State. If this does not happen, fraudsters choose the Member State with the weakest RMS for their crimes.
The tax losses caused by Europe-wide VAT fraud do not necessarily affect the Member State in which the initiator resides.
Any other Member State involved in the fraud can be affected.
This is why there should be a European exchange of experience on the RMS.
Selected results from the audit of individual sales In the context of the parallel tests, the NK and BRH examined the quality and usefulness of information on selected deliveries and / or
The international exchange of information between the financial administrations of the Czech Republic and Germany.
In addition, the two tax authorities jointly examined the execution of several deliveries, about which there were doubts, or which the tax authorities of both states explained differently in the tax returns or ZM.
At the request of the BRH, the NCA examined a total of eight transactions between eight Czech and eight German tax collectors.
In addition, in 43 cases, on the basis of notices from the BRH, the NCA examined the values of intra-Community transactions with Germany, which Czech tax collectors had indicated in their tax returns and ZM.
At the request of the NCO, the BRH reviewed a total of 23 deliveries between 23 German and 21 Czech tax collectors.
The relevant information was exchanged exclusively on the basis of Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003 on the CLO.
The examination of the selected cases showed, among other things, that the different registration procedures in the EC Member States lead to the problems mentioned in Chapter 4.1:
1.
According to MIAS data, a Czech tax collector purchased €60,500 worth of goods from a German tax collector in the third quarter of 2004.
When the Czech tax collector declared a purchase of only €29,869, the Czech tax administration sent a request for information to Germany in order to check the value of the delivered goods.
The German side indicated in its reply to the Czech request for information that the German tax collector in question had delivered goods worth €27,381 to its Czech business partner in the second quarter of 2004, €31,997 in the third quarter and €10,276 in the fourth quarter.
Furthermore, the answer showed that the VAT ID number of the German tax collector was not valid until 28 September 2004. However, the German CLO had accepted a further application from the German tax authority and had brought forward the validity of the VAT ID number retroactively to 1 May 2004.
The German tax officer corrected the ZM.
Based on this information, it was a (intra-Community) purchase of goods by the Czech tax collector.
By way of a request to the competent tax office in the Czech Republic, the NCA found that in 2004 the Czech tax collector had made supplementary VAT returns for the individual (under-age) tax periods in which he declared a higher value of purchases from other Member States and at the same time sought the deduction of VAT from purchases from other Member States.
On the basis of these additional VAT declarations, the responsible clerk of the Czech tax office could not clearly determine whether the value of the deliveries of the above-mentioned German supplier was included in the declared purchases.
In response to a request for information from the NCA, the BRH found that the German supplier had been registered as subject to turnover tax in September 2003.
At the time of registration, however, he had not ever applied for the allocation of a VAT ID number, but only for a tax number that finally applied to Germany.
Although it is usually not possible in Germany to retroactively assign a VAT ID number to a person subject to tax, in 2006 the responsible clerk of the German financial administration did so retroactively to 1 May 2004.
The German CLO allocates a VAT ID number retroactively if the German operator has not caused the delayed allocation; for example, if the CLO caused the delay following the request of the tax authority for the issuance of a VAT ID No.
In this case, the CLO will issue the VAT ID number retroactively, because the entrepreneur does not require a valid VAT ID number for an intra-Community delivery in accordance with § 6 UStG.
Conversely, a German purchaser does not need the (valid) VAT ID number of its supplier to explain the intra-Community acquisition.
Due to these procedural differences between the Member States, the German CLO issued the VAT ID number in this particular case retroactively.
2.
As part of the international exchange of information, the Czech finance official asked for the verification of the German entrepreneur's VAT registration.
According to the MIAS data, the date of registration is March 5, 2005, while a registration certificate issued by the local German FA indicates October 1, 2004.
The German authorities announced in their reply that the German tax practitioner was registered on 1 October 2004, but for organisational reasons was not allocated a VAT ID number in Germany until 16 February 2005.
In response to a request from the local Czech Treasury official, the NCO learned that the tax officer had carried out a VAT audit for the tax periods from the third quarter of 2004 to the second quarter of 2005.
On this examination, the tax office found that the Czech tax collector had declared in his VAT return services worth CZK 9,897, which he had provided to the German tax collectors before their VAT registration (i.e. before 1 October 2004).
The (Czech) tax office set a tax debt of CZK 1,880 for the third quarter of 2004 against the Czech tax payer.
In response to the question from the NK, the BRH found that the German tax collector had only been allocated the VAT ID number when he registered his company, which was founded in 2004, with the FA on 16 February 2005.
In addition, the FA registered him retroactively from 1 October 200415 for VAT purposes in order to be able to monitor the submission of the VAT declaration for 2004.
In this VAT declaration, the tax collector gave intra-Community purchases from the Czech Republic in the value of 160 €(about 5.000 CZK).
3. In his sales tax declaration for September 2004 and in his ZM for the third quarter of 2004, a Czech tax collector gave goods worth CZK 114,615 to a German tax collector.
When checking the registration of the German tax collector in the MIAS system, the Czech finance official found that this registration was not valid until 11 November 2004 and thus after the goods had been shipped to Germany.
The Czech tax collector made a supplementary VAT declaration in which he declared sales from domestic deliveries worth CZK 114,615 and VAT of CZK 21,777, which he paid.
Through a request to the local FA in the Czech Republic, the NCCC found that the Czech tax collector subsequently submitted an application to reopen the tax procedure in the case of the supplementary VAT declaration. As evidence, he submitted a confirmation to the German tax administration that the German tax collector had been registered since 1 January 2000.
Accordingly, the Czech finance official checked the validity of the registration of the German tax person in the context of international exchange of information.
According to the German information, the German tax collector was not allocated a VAT ID number until 11 November 2004, i.e. after the date of the delivery of the goods.
As a result, the Czech finance official rejected the request to reopen the tax procedure.
The BRH found that in this case there had been no intra-Community purchase of goods, because the German tax collector had only received a VAT ID number on 11 November 2004.
The German recipient, however, declared both the acquisition as an intra-Community purchase and the value-added tax and also demanded the refund of pre-taxes at the same level.
Because this did not lead to a change in the amount of the tax debt of the German tax collector, the German finance official did not correct the information in the VAT declaration.
The BRH also noted that the company of the German tax collector mentioned in the request for information was changed during the processing of the answer in Germany, which led to confusion between two German tax collectors.
This change in the name of the German tax collector also confused the Czech finance official.
4.
As part of the international exchange of information, the German finance official reviewed the purchase of goods in the first quarter of 2005 by a Czech tax collector from a German tax collector worth €22,686.
Through a request from the local tax officer in the Czech Republic, the NKKA found that the Czech tax officer had examined, during an external audit of the Czech tax authority, whether the intra-Community delivery had actually taken place and whether the Czech tax collector had recorded and paid the bill for the delivery of the goods.
The Czech tax collector did not explain the intrinsically bad acquisition in his VAT declaration, because the German supplier did not indicate his VAT ID number in the invoice, but only his tax number, which is intended for business within Germany.
According to the MIAS data, the German tax collector will not be registered for VAT in connection with intra-Community transactions until 21 April 2005, i.e. after delivery to the Czech tax collector.
The Czech finance official also requested that the German financial administration send a copy of the registration certificate of the German tax collector, so that if necessary he could initiate a corresponding tax procedure.
The Czech FA considered this business to be the purchase of goods from a non-entrepreneurial (private) person in Germany and therefore did not impose a VAT on the purchase of the goods from Germany.
The BRH found that under German law, a tax collector who delivers goods to other Member States does not have to have a VAT ID number for intra-Community deliveries in order to be able to claim the VAT exemption for such a delivery.
The supplier must only have the purchaser's VAT number in the other Member State and must be able to prove the transport of the goods in question to the other Member State.
In this case, the turnover under German tax law is a (tax-exempt) intra-Community supply, which should be subject to employment taxation in the Czech Republic.
In any case, it is important that the Czech finance officer took note of this business incident, because the delivery of a machine of this value did not belong to the core business of the German supplier.
As described in section 4.6.2, the German CLO refuses requests for information on intra-Community transactions if they are below the minimum amount of €15,000: 5.
According to MIAS data, a Czech tax collector purchased €12,561 worth of goods from a German tax collector in the third quarter of 2004.
The Czech financial officer carried out an audit for this period of taxation.
As part of the intergovernmental assistance, the Czech financial administration requested the verification of the delivery of the goods by means of a SCAC form.
The Czech tax collector said that he had not received the goods, had never been in contact with the German company and that the purchase of the goods in question had not been booked with him.
