12.
As part of the international exchange of information, the German financial administration requested verification of the delivery of goods and the provision of services in the third quarter of 2005 by means of a SCACVordruck.
According to the request for information, the Czech tax collector had in the period in question supplied the German tax collector with a total value of €396,126 and provided services worth €11,885.
The NCA found that the Czech tax administration had carried out an audit of the Czech tax collector in order to investigate the delivery.
In response to the request for information, the Czech financial administration announced that the Czech tax collector had delivered and installed a production facility to the German company.
The Czech tax officer supplied the individual parts of the production plant before the Czech Republic's accession to the EC and the production plant was installed on the basis of the order after 1 May 2004.
The German tax collector did not remove the assembled production line and claimed defects.
In the third quarter of 2005, the Czech tax collector charged the German the production plant for €107,100 and €11,885 for services.
The German tax collector received the rebates, but did not recognize them and did not pay them.
In response to a request from the local finance officer in the Czech Republic, the NCCC found that all invoices had been properly recorded on the books of the Czech tax collector.
The VAT returns for the third quarter of 2005 included only the amounts documented by the Czech tax collector and related to invoices invoiced after the first of May 2004.
The BRH found that the local FA came to the conclusion, on the basis of the response of the Czech financial administration, that these transactions were a uniform (goods) delivery of the Czech tax collector to the German one, including the assembly done.
In this particular case, the place of fulfilment for this so-called factory delivery is the place where the production plant is installed.
The German recipient of the work delivery owes the sales tax according to the German VAT law.
At the same time, the recipient can claim a deduction of the same amount.
The German FA did not correct the VAT declaration, as the German tax authority's liability for turnover remained unchanged.
13. According to MIAS data, Czech tax collector A purchased a machine worth €58,000 from German tax collector C. in February 2005.
The Czech finance official sent a request for verification of this information to Germany.
In response to the request for information, the German side announced that the German tax collector C had delivered the machine in 2004 to the Czech tax collector B, who returned it to the German tax collector C in October 2004.
According to the German financial administration, the machine was not transported back to Germany, but to the branch of the German tax authority C in the Czech Republic.
In response to the request for information, it also emerged that the German tax collector C had delivered the machine to the Czech tax collector A in February 2005.
He received the machine at the headquarters of the German tax collector's office in the Czech Republic.
Since this delivery (from C to A) took place only within the Czech Republic, there was no common delivery of goods.
By way of a request to the local tax officer responsible for fiscal B, the NCA found that according to MIAS data, in the third quarter of 2004, the German tax accountant C had delivered goods worth €88,027 to the Czech tax collector (another machine).
Tax officer B said he did not receive the goods, so the local Czech finance official sent a request for information to Germany.
The answer was that the machine had been delivered.
In the course of further investigations into the tax collector B, the tax officer found that the machine, worth €88,027, had not been registered with the tax collector B and that it could be the same type of machine as the branch of the German tax collector C had delivered to the Czech tax collector A in February 2005.
The NCA also found that the Czech tax officer in charge of tax-dodging A had carried out an audit of the latter.
The financial officer had the invoice of the German tax authority C of 7 February 2005, in which the tax person A is to be specified as the recipient of the machine.
The Czech finance official noted that tax collector A had not recorded this bill.
Tax officer A had signed a lease agreement with another Czech company, whose object was a machine of the same type.
The leasing company delivered the machine on February 9, 2005 and also provided transport.
The Czech FA did not use the information provided in the reply to the request for information to determine the tax liability of tax collector A.
The BRH found that the German tax collector C had delivered the machine, worth €88,027, not to the Czech Republic, but to another German tax collector D.
Accordingly, there was no intra-Community delivery of goods, but a tax-compliant delivery within Germany.
Consequently, the German finance official did not recognise the claim of the German tax authority C on VAT exemption and corrected the information in his tax return.
German tax collector D delivered the machine to Czech tax collector B.
According to German law, this delivery was not subject to tax in Germany, but was subject to VAT in the Czech Republic.
The BRH also found that the German tax accountant C, in his ZM for the first quarter of 2005, had indicated the delivery of a machine worth €58,000 to the Czech tax collector A.
This delivery was not checked during the German FA's tax audit.
