17.
In the fourth quarter of 2004, the German tax collector delivered €11,600 worth of goods to the German tax collector.
As part of the interstate exchange of information, the German finance official asked for a check on whether the mentioned Czech tax collectors actually existed, since the alleged owner of the German tax collectors had created a number of false claims in Germany.
In the course of the FA's review of the operation, the Czech tax collector confirmed the purchase of the goods.
According to the Czech tax authority, the goods were not delivered from Germany to the Czech Republic, but were resold in Germany in 2005.
The Czech tax collector presented evidence of the sale in January 2005.
The Czech tax collector was not registered as subject to turnover tax in Germany and did not tax the sale of the goods in the Czech Republic or in Germany.
All these facts pointed to tax evasion within Germany, and the Czech finance official provided these details in his reply to the request for information to the German financial administration.
In a request to the local Czech tax officer, the NCO stated that the Czech tax collector had made a supplementary tax return for the fourth quarter of 2004, in which he declared, among other things, the value of the goods he had purchased from a German tax collector and at the same time asserted the right to deduct VAT on purchases from other Member States.
In his Czech VAT declaration, he did not declare any sales tax on the sale of goods in Germany.
On the basis of a supplementary VAT declaration, which was issued after the external audit, the Czech financial officer determined the value added tax debt unchanged.
According to Czech legislation, in this case, there was no acquisition of goods from other Member States, as the goods were not shipped or transported from another Member State to the Czech Republic.
Thus, the Czech Treasury official drew a false conclusion in the external audit.
The BRH found that immediately after receiving the reply to the request for information, which showed that the goods had not left Germany, the German tax officer corrected the tax return and demanded the payment of sales tax of €1,600.
In addition, the competent FA sent a control notice to the FA responsible for the actual recipient of the goods to ensure that the resale of these goods is properly taxed.
