18.
The Czech finance official received a request for information from the German financial administration on whether the Czech tax collector had purchased a car worth €47,400 from the German tax collector in February 2005.
A copy of the VAT registration certificate of the Czech tax collector was attached to the request for information.
As a further attachment, a photocopy of the passport was attached to the person who was to have transferred the vehicle.
In the course of his investigation, the Czech financial officer discovered that the passport had been stolen, that the person named in it had not introduced a vehicle to the Czech Republic and indicated that he had no contacts with a German tax collector.
The VAT registration certificate, the print of which was sent by the German side, was not issued by the Czech financial administration.
With this information, the Czech finance official responded to the request for information and said at the same time that he could not confirm the purchase of the car.
In a request to the local Czech financial officer, the NKKähr stated that the Czech tax collector does not have his registered office at the address indicated in the commercial register and that the company's managing director is not available.
After a tax appeal procedure for the tax period of February 2005, the Czech Treasury official determined the tax debt of the Czech tax collector to be zero.
In the course of a further investigation, the Czech financial officer found that the vehicle in question had been sold to another Czech person who had purchased it on the basis of an internet advertisement.
The BRH found that the local German finance official had refused the claim of the German tax authority to exempt this supply from the VAT on the basis of the Czech response to the request for information.
19. In the course of an external audit, a German FA was not able to clarify a difference of €3,000 between the value of the purchased goods indicated in the VAT declaration and the reported values from other Member States.
A Czech tax collector should have delivered goods worth €89,424 to a German tax collector in the fourth quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005.
Since the acquisition declared by the German tax authority was not in accordance with the MIAS data, the German finance official requested the verification of the deliveries and their payment within the framework of the interstate exchange of information.
In his reply to the request for information, the Czech finance official indicated that the only managing director of the Czech company had been removed from the commercial register on 8 July 2005 and that a new managing director had not yet been registered.
The German recipient of the goods was presumed to be a relative of the Czech company's shareholder.
The Czech tax collector issued a VAT return and a ZM, which, after the deletion of the managing director in the commercial register, was signed by an unauthorised person, namely this shareholder of the company.
The accountant of the Czech tax collector informed the financial officer that the owner of the capital had paid the payment in euros to the company's account for the goods invoiced.
Cash receipts have not been issued.
In a request to the local Czech FA, the NK stated that the financial officer had recognised the Czech tax authority's claim to VAT exemption for shipments of goods to other Member States, worth CZK 1,326,307 in the first quarter of 2004 and CZK 1,416,180 in the first quarter of 2005.
The BRH found that the German tax officer did not correct the German purchaser's VAT declaration, since in the meantime a German court had confirmed the insolvency of the German tax collector.
Since the previous external audit showed no evidence of tax fraud, there was no prospect of actually being able to collect a fixed VAT debt.
20. According to MIAS data, a German tax collector purchased goods from the Czech Republic worth €4,251,196 in 2005, after which he had purchased goods worth €43,274 the previous year.
The German tax collector did not declare the intra-Community purchases in his 2004 VAT declaration or in the 2005 one.
In addition, he did not explain the value of the initial sales.
Due to these discrepancies, the German FA submitted a request for information regarding the 4th quarter 2005 and the 1st quarter 2006.
In the ZM for these two quarters, a Czech supplier reported intra-Community shipments of goods with a total value of CZK 167,246,083.
On 6 September 2006, the request for information was received, in which the German side requested to check whether the delivery reported by the Czech tax authority had actually taken place.
In response to this request for information, the Czech financial administration said that the German request could not be met because the Czech company does not have a managing director (or other legal representative).
Documents provided to the NCA by the competent financial officer show that on 30 March 2006, together with the managing director of the Czech tax authority, a protocol for the commencement of the sales tax audit for the 4th quarter 2004 and the period January to December 2005 was drawn up.
At the same time, the tax officer asked the tax officer to provide all accounting and tax documents for this period, but omitted to do so.
According to the Commercial Register, the term of office of the only managing director expired on 16 May 2005 without the appointment of a new managing director.
The Czech tax collector has not issued any tax returns since April 2006.
As part of the parallel investigation, the NCA, in cooperation with the BRH, investigated several cases of intra-Community deliveries between the Czech Republic and Germany, which were not the subject of a prior exchange of information between the two countries.
The two courts of auditors exchanged information on the cases under review via the CLO of both countries.
21. A Czech company (UCR), which is not based in Germany, informed the competent FA (Chemnitz-Süd) that it wanted to conduct tax-deductible business in Germany.
Based on this information, the company was registered in June 2005, but did not receive a German VAT ID.
The (UCR) accepted an order from a Danish company (UDK) for the production of wind turbines and their delivery to Austria in the name, at the risk and for the account of the Danish customer.
Due to insufficient manufacturing capacity, the Danish company passed on part of the order to a German tax collector (UDE) based in Germany.
The following figure shows the contractual relationship and the transport route of the wind turbines:
According to German law, the place of performance of these transactions must be determined as described below:
- The Danish company (UDK) sent the wind turbines to Austria in its name, at its own risk and for its own installation bill.
Due to the assembly, its delivery takes place in Austria, i.e. the delivery of the wind turbines is controllable in Austria.
- Because the carrier was commissioned by the Danish company (UDK) and the latter had the transport carried out in its own name, at its own risk and for its own account, the delivery of the German sub-contractor (UDE) is where the transport began, i.e. in Germany.
Although the wind turbines were delivered to another EC Member State (AU) and the recipient is registered as tax-compliant in an EC Member State (CR), no tax exemption could be claimed for the delivery of the German sub-contractor (UDE), since the EC Member State for which the delivery was intended is a different country from the seat of the Czech business19.
Accordingly, the delivery will be properly taxed in Germany and the Czech company (UCR) has claimed the deduction in its VAT returns.
The location of the Czech company's (UCR) delivery also depends on where the transport began.
However, some of the wind turbines were transported from the Czech Republic and others from Germany.
- The delivery of wind turbines produced in the Czech Republic took place in the Czech Republic.
- The delivery of the remaining wind turbines produced in Germany took place in Germany.
Accordingly, the Czech company (UCR) provided both intra-Community deliveries from the Czech Republic to Austria and intra-Community deliveries from Germany to Austria.
The BRH found that the Czech company (UCR) did not declare intra-Community deliveries in its German tax returns or in its ZM made against the German CLO.
Thus, the Czech company may have uniformly treated all its intra-Community deliveries as intra-Community deliveries from the Czech Republic.
The NCP found that (UCR) did not report intra-Community deliveries to Austria, but intra-Community deliveries to Denmark.
In order to secure the taxation of intra-Community purchases in Austria, the cooperation of at least four financial administrations (Austrian, Czech, Danish and German) would be necessary, although in this case there is no evidence of tax fraud or tax evasion.
In addition, the NCA and the BRH reviewed case studies to show the size of the differences between the information in the VAT returns and the MIAS data caused by the different laws of 2004.
The cases also show that it takes some time for tax collectors and tax collectors to apply the new legal requirements:
22. In his ZM for the second, third and fourth quarters of 2004, a Czech tax person reported shipments of goods with a total value of CZK 792,977,452 to a German tax collector.
In the same period, another Czech tax collector reported in his ZM intra-Community deliveries to another German tax collector for a total value of CZK 18,157,265.
According to the information provided by the BRH to the NCBs, both cases involved the supply of electricity.
Both Czech tax collectors took into account the above-mentioned deliveries according to the Czech law no. 235 / 2004, which is in force in 2004.
In a further examination of these transactions, an audit group of the NK found that in 2004 there were different legal requirements regarding the supply or purchase of electrical energy between the Czech Republic and Germany.
Whereas in the Czech Republic the tax collectors declared the supplies of electrical energy in accordance with the provisions of the law No. 235 / 2004, valid in 2004, as intra-Community deliveries of goods, according to the German legal regulations in 2004, it was not a intra-Community purchase of goods, but taxable and taxable transactions in Germany.
The differences in the legal provisions were eliminated in the Czech Republic by the adoption of Law No. 635 / 2004, which changed some tax provisions with effect from 1 January 2005.
23. During the examination of intra-Community deliveries or purchases in cooperation with the BRH, it was further established that a Czech tax collector in his ZM for the first and fourth quarters of 2005 made intra-Community deliveries to a German tax collector in the total value of CZK 240,411,163 and another Czech tax collector in his ZM for the same period made intra-Community deliveries to another German tax collector in the value of CZ73,70,776.
The information provided by the BRH to the NCBs showed that in both cases it was a matter of supplies of electrical energy.
In accordance with the wording of Law no. 235 / 2004, which will apply from 1 January 2005, the place of performance for which the purchaser has its legal domicile, registered office or establishment for which this delivery is made is the place of performance for which the purchaser has its legal seat, registered office or establishment.
For this reason, the Czech tax authorities should not have specified the electricity supplies in their 2005 ZM.
In MIAS, the fact that both operators treated the supply of electrical energy in their ZM as intra-Community supplies resulted in a difference of CZK 503,881,939.
Closing note
Through the cooperation, the goals of the BRH and the NK have been achieved.
Both courts have gained in-depth knowledge of VAT administration systems in the Czech Republic and Germany.
The cooperation revealed differences in the two systems and in the legal regulations governing VAT administration.
During the parallel tests, interesting cases of intra-Community deliveries or purchases were revealed.
For some of them, further observation is worth it.
On the basis of the audit results, both audit courts drew up recommendations for the management of the turnover tax.
The follow-up of these recommendations in the form of a review should be part of the follow-up.
The new experience and knowledge gained through the cooperation of both courts of auditors form the basis for the successful execution of future audits in the area of VAT administration.
